class Solution {
    public List<List<Integer>> combine(int n, int k) {
        List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
        dfs(n, k, new ArrayList<Integer>(), result);
        return result;
    }

    private void dfs(int n, int k, List<Integer> curr, List<List<Integer>> result) {
        if (k == 0) {
            result.add(new ArrayList<>(curr));
            return;
        }

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            curr.add(i);
            dfs(n, k - 1, curr, result);
            curr.remove(curr.size() - 1);
        }
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n^k)
space complexity: O(n^k)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:
We use a recursive function (dfs) to generate all combinations. The base case is when k becomes 0, which means we have used all numbers. In the recursive part, we iterate from 1 to n and for each number, add it to the current combination, call the function recursively with k decremented, and then remove the last number from the combination. This ensures that we generate all combinations and avoid duplicates.

